deck_excerpt: Silenforc with Setup for Vortex Omni-Negate
deck_description:
***This deck is meant for MasterDuel once it releases. Hope you enjoy the ideas in it though.

In reality, Silenforc is probably better with just one Pendulumgraph and no other pendulum package. The point of the deck is to get 1 Pendulumgraph into the hand with the Luster Pendulum, usually by opening with Duelist Alliance (I'll refer to it as DA), and using Silenforc effects to get Pendulumgraph in hand. After that, pendulum zon Pendulumgraph, use DA, and then pendulum zone Luster. Pop Pendulumgraph with Luster effect to get a pendulum in the Extra Deck. From there, the second Pendulumgraph gets added to hand and will most likely be Ritual Summoned. As a result, it allows for Pendulumgraph's spell/trap negate to go off and then special summon Vortex with omni-negate online.

The goal is to get Duelist Alliance in hand (via pot, new Saffira draw, opening, etc.) as Silenforc has a pretty easy time getting Pendulumgraph into the hand. I feel like Silenforc with a singular Pendulumgraph has plenty of interrupts (spell/trap negate, omni-negate, special summon bounce, targeting effect negate, and pops via continuous trap), but having an extra omni-negate set up should the draw be slightly weak or the opponent has a lot of handtraps can alleviate some issues.

That being said, the combo is slightly clunky by introducing 4 potential bricks to the deck. While new Saffira isn't amazing, I feel like her draw effect can help get ride of any brick for 1-2 better cards. I do enjoy the added flavor to the deck though besides the drawbacks.

Once again in my never-ending crusade to make my favorite archetypes cook in ways I never thought possible, I have found the best way to play Gameciel Turbo! Now, the concept of this deck is simple, go into Gameciel with Kyoutou Waterfront and bully our opponent with well-timed non one per turn omni-negates. However, because Konami won't give Kaijus anymore support (hopefully for now), our best shot of playing Kyoutou are opening it, Terraforming, or Ancient Fairy Dragon and because Kaijus are limited by their own summon clause, Saryuja Skull Dread is our best friend.

Now what deck can link climb, synchro summon, AND search Kyoutou? Why Crusadia, of course! With two card combos that can end on two Link 4s, this deck has the sauce to get the job done. And of course, because its me, I got a nice, little tech that gasses up the deck surprisingly well. The honorary Crusadia monsters Parallel eXceed and Link Infra-Flier are perfect for the deck and searchable with Cynet Mining for the latter, giving the deck functionally 8 more Crusadia monsters to extend with, which means tehnically one Crusadia name is full combo with one of those cards.

The deck isn't the best, of course. The right number of negates can shut it down and that stupid rock is a thorn in its side, but if it can pop-off, it's a threat to behold. Not to mention it cheap, so you could cook it up for a relatively low price. What Kaijus you use outside of Gameciel (if any at all) is up to you all. I could see Radian popping up as a free Link-2 with Kyoutou in play, I just like the idea of controling with the Kaiju counter abilities.

The deck features cards used by Kaiba towards the end of the Battle City arc, including support for his Blue-Eyes White Dragons, his infamous Virus Cards as well as the first monsters in the VWXYZ series he used in his duel against Yugi Muto in the Semi Finals of his Battle City tournament. It also introduces "Shrink" to the OCG.

deck_excerpt: D.D. Battlefield FTK ft. Land Flipping + Lantron
deck_description:
Good day to you! Did you know there is a spell which acts as Shien's Spy but for field spells in a way? Land Flipping is the name and I didn't know until I got it from Legacy Pack. So, I decided to give it a shot with D.D. Battlefield to burn the opponent but one can also use Chicken Game or Extra Net for draw reasons as well. Anyways, it's time to teach you how to guide this deck.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place "D.D. Battlefield" to your side. Then, give it to your opponent with "Land Flipping".

2) Special Summon Lantron with Saryuja and Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability. Then, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone to setup your Primal Seed loop.

3) Clear everything but Chaos + Lantron with Offerings. Then, play Tri-Wight to pull out 3 x Level 1 dudes.

4) Time to start XYZ Summon. Here is the order: Dullahan >>> Mischief >>> Barian into Utopia >>> Justice >>> Gaia...

  • There is also another alternative pack you can give it a try, which is included in "Side Deck". Remove Barian to add Chalice and XYZ Summon from left to right. Then, end it with Draco Future >>> Chalice >>> Offerings combo.

5) If you summon in this order, each time you XYZ Summon, you would take 500 dmg due to "D.D. Battlefield". However, thanks to Lantron, you can reflect it right back at your opponent. Therefore, you can deal 500 x 5 = 2500 dmg in total.

6) Destroy Gaia with Offerings. Then, shuffle these 5 x XYZ monsters with "Pot of Avarice" and return two cards you drew back to your deck with "Pot of Generosity" to make a continuous loop.

7) Repeat starting from #3 to #6 until the opponent is dead.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Number 21" + "Land Flipping" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 60 UR!

- "Ghostrick Dullahan" + "Ghostrick Angel of Mischief" can be found within "Mischievous Specters" Secret Pack to save 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

So, a while ago, I made a Nightingale Burn deck which was complex but can take as many turns as you like to finish your opponent. This time, I decided to convert it into FTK so you can burn your opponent in one fell swoop.

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, bring out Swallow and play "Cattle Call" to replace it with Nightingale and give her to opposing side with Shien's Spy. If your opponent's side is full, "Back to Square One" can spare one for you.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup your Primal Seed loop.

3) With Monster Reborn + Back to Square One + Polymerization, arrange for your needs and...

  • First, bring forth "Starving Venemy Dragon" by using Dissolver only in-hand and any DARK monster but Chaos Emperor from anywhere as materials.
  • Next is "Starving Venom Fusion Dragon" by using 2 x DARK monsters from your field. "Monster Reborn" is your friend and don't use Venemy + Chaos as materials by accident. Also, increase the level of Nightingale to 5 with "Star Changer", which allows you to copycat Nightingale with Starving Venom.
  • Then, revive Dissolver with "Monster Reborn" and use the ability of Dissolver to bring forth "Odd-Eyes Venom Dragon" by using Starving Venom + Dissolver as materials. No need for "Polymerization" and revive Starving Venom back with "Monster Reborn".
  • Finally, bring forth "Supreme King Dragon Starving Venom" by using Odd-Eyes + Venemy as materials. No need for "Polymerization".

4) If you have done everything correct, you can start pulling the trigger with Venemy + Fusion + Odd-Eyes. If you still need more burn, apply with Supreme at last for good measure, with a total of 4000 + 4000 + 4000 + 5000 = 17000 damage for the FTK.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 690 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Move over Bystial Runick, the OG deck that pairs incredibly well with Runick is still good despite it's nerfs, and that is Spright!
deck_description:
Move over Bystial Runick, the OG deck that pairs incredibly well with Runick is still good despite it's nerfs, and that is Spright!

The ridiculously strong combination of Spright and Runick's smothering control and endless grind game create a deck that all strategies would have to fear and respect. Sprights ending on 3-5 interruptions (Sprind's bounce, Red's monster negate, Carrot's S/T negate, Smasher's banish, and I:P Masquerena's quick link) combined with Runick's draw 3 and multiple quick play spells generally stop any deck cold in their tracks. Both archetypes combined have a potential 10+ interruptions for your opponent to slog through, while maintaining a superior resource loop - outpacing most other strategies!

 
If you want to win and reach Masters 1 in Masterduel with a relentlessly strong resource-oriented control strategy, you've chosen to pilot the correct deck!

If you want a detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, check out my article from a couple months ago.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!


GLHF Duelists!

neste deck não usei as cartas "sábio com azul nos olhos" e "maquina de bingo, vai!!!" porque sao cartas caras no momento. Tambem não usei cartas do arquetipo "bystial" pelo mesmo motivo.

 

O objetivo do deck é invocar muitos monstros level 8 para fazer xyz. Tente enviar "Dragão jato de olhos azuis" para o cemitério ou pegue-o para mão o quanto antes, pois destruindo um card no campo, ele pode ser invocado.

Se vier em sua mao "trocar", "a melodia do despertar dos Dragão", "santuario do Dragão", "najestade com azul nos olhos" e "ravina de dragões", use por ultimo a carta "trocar", para evitar que voce compre uma carta que pode buscar usando as outras cartas.

Inglês: I hope you like the deck. In this deck I didn't use the cards "wise man with blue in his eyes" and "bingo machine, go!!!" because they are expensive cards at the moment. I also didn't use cards from the "bystial" archetype for the same reason. The objective of the deck is to summon many level 8 monsters to do xyz. Try sending "Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon" to the Graveyard or take it into your hand as soon as possible, as by destroying a card on the field, it can be Summoned. If "switch", "the melody of Dragon awakening", "Dragon sanctuary", "najesty with blue in her eyes" and "dragon ravine" come into your hand, use the "switch" card last to avoid you draw a card that you can search for using the other cards.

deck_excerpt: Ancient cards getting brand new support!
deck_description:
The main deck is missing three copies of Ancient Gear Tanker because it has not been added to this website yet. The three Kuribohs are placeholders for Tanker.

The new support has made the deck much more consistent and has given you options in what you can do. You have many paths to take depending on the cards you draw, and even if you're negated, you can still push through and get something on the field.

The playstyle of Ancient Gears has changed with this new support. Yes, it's still an OTK deck about getting a big boss monster on the field, but now the deck has a lot more strategy to it and a lot more routes it can take. The deck can overcome some negation now, and it is a lot more consistent. In the past, I only ran one or two Ancient Gear Golems, because they weren't that big of a focus. I would only ever use them with Ancient Gear Fusion. Now, you can flood the field with them and do a lot more with them... Mostly because Ancient Gear Dark Golem is so good haha.

 

Gameplan:

1. The first thing you'll want to do is to put Ancient Gear Fortress on the field if you have it. If you don't have it, you can always prosperity to try to get it. You'll also want to place Geartown on the field if you have it, and if you don't have it but only have Terraforming then you'll use Terraforming to get Geartown. If you're not able to get Geartown on the field at this point, then jump to Step 5. If you don't have Ancient Gear Wyvern but you do have both Geartown and you have Ancient Gear Catapult, then skip to Step 4. I also usually use Pot of Prosperity here to search for Ancient Gear Advance, Geartown, or Fortress depending on what I already have.

2. After you put Fortress on the field (or you at least tried), you want to normal summon Ancient Gear Wyvern. You activate Wyvern's effect and you'll tutor for a different card depending on what's in your hand. If you do not have Ancient Gear Catapult or Ancient Gear Advance, then you'll tutor for Ancient Gear Advance. Even if you do have Catapult, Advance is a required card to add to your hand. If you didn't have Ancient Gear Fortress already, but you were able to get it through Prosperity, then search for Fortress here and activate it as soon as you can. If you already have Advance and Fortress in your hand, then you'll tutor for Ancient Gear Box. After getting Box, you'll activate it's effect from your hand to target Ancient Gear Frame. You could also search for Ancient Gear Commander, but you'll end up getting Commander later, so it isn't that helpful to get it now.

3. If you followed the previous steps successfully, you'll want to activate Ancient Gear Advance. You will search for Ancient Gear Catapult with it's activated effect (If you already have Catapult in your hand, then you'll search for either Ancient Gear Fusion or Ancient Gear Duel. It doesn't really matter which one you add to your hand, but I usually go for Duel.). You'll then use Advance's second effect to destroy Ancient Gear Wyvern. You don't want any monsters on the field so you're able to activate Catapult.

4. After having no monsters on the field, you will activate Ancient Gear Catapult and target Geartown. Special summon Ancient Gear Commander with Geartown's effect and Ancient Gear Dark Golem with Ancient Gear Catapult's effect. When Ancient Gear Dark Golem is summoned, you'll want to tutor for Ancient Gear Tanker and Ancient Gear Duel. You'll discard Box if you have it, but if you never got Box then you can discard anything except for Tanker and Duel. If you didn't have Wyvern previously, then you can go into Wyvern instead of Commander, but it isn't advised to go into Wyvern instead. At this point, if you have Urgent Schedule, then you can activate it now if you haven't and if your opponent has more monsters than you. You can put the other Dark Golem on the field and another level 4 body. Use these cards to link or XYZ summon, because they take up space on the board. The second Dark Golem can bring you into Aegaion the Sea Castrum later if you think it would be useful, but I would wait until later and summon Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star later after I've fusion summoned my win condition.

5. Activate Ancient Gear Commander's effect to add an Ancient Gear Golem to the graveyard from your deck. Special summon Ancient Gear Tanker from your hand with Commander's effect. With Tanker summoned, you'll use it's effect to summon Ancient Gear Golem from your graveyard if your opponent controls a monster. If your opponent does not control a monster, then summon Ancient Gear Golem or Ancient Gear Dark Golem from your hand. If you don't have either, then just summon whatever you can.

6. If you have another Geartown in your hand or a Terraforming to get another Geartown, then activate it now. Activate Ancient Gear Tanker's effect to target Geartown, and add either Ancient Gear Frame or Ancient Gear Dark Golem to the field (If you already have Ancient Gear Fusion, then add Ancient Gear Dark Golem to the field, but if you don't have Ancient Gear Fusion, then summon Ancient Gear Frame.). If you summon Frame here, then activate it's effect to discard a card and add Ancient Gear Fusion to your hand. If you added Dark Golem to the field and you already had Ancient Gear Fusion in your hand, then just proceed to Step 7.

7. Link summon Ancient Gear Ballista with Ancient Gear Commander and either Ancient Gear Frame or Tanker. Add Geartown to your hand with Ballista. If your opponent has a monster on the field, then use Ballista's effect to target your opponent's monster and set it's stats to zero. Target Geartown with your destruction from Ballista. With this Geartown, repeat the actions in Step 6 if you weren't able to pop Geartown then. If you were able to pop Geartown in Step 6 then add Ancient Gear Dark Golem to the field from your if you don't already have it. If you do already have both copies on the field, then search for anything you want, but I would personally search for Ancient Gear Hunting Hound just in case one of my fusions gets negated or if I'm not able to get a fusion.

8. Activate Ancient Gear Fusion from your hand and use Ancient Gear Golem as fusion material on the field and use three fusion material from the deck to summon Chaos Ancient Gear Giant. Activate Ancient Gear Commander's effect from the graveyard to banish it so you can activate Ancient Gear Duel without having to set. Activate Ancient Geat Duel's effect and target Ancient Gear Dark Golem and two other Ancient Gear monsters from your graveyard to fusion summon Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem from your extra deck. If you have extra level 8 monsters (which can happen), then you can either go into Aegaion if you think it would be useful or you can summon Dingirsu. Aegaion can be used to remove a big monster your opponent has on the field that may become a problem in the battle phase, for example.

9. At this point, your cards should be unable to be targeted by your opponent's card effects due to your Ancient Gear Fortress, your cards that have the text, "Ancient Gear Golem", in them are unaffected by your opponent's monster effects due to Ancient Gear Duel. Your Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem can attack up to three times in the battle phase, and it inflicts piercing damage to your opponent's defense position monsters. Chaos Ancient Gear Giant can attack all of your opponent's monsters and it inflicts piercing damage.

10. Go into battle phase and attack all of your opponent's monsters with Chaos Ancient Gear Giant. If their lifepoints still haven't depleted, then you attack them with Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem three times. If this doesn't kill them, then they're cheating.

 

If negated:

If your opponent sets up spell and trap removal and removes Fortress, then you'll try your best ot get Fortess back. If you started the game with Fortress in your hand, then in Step 2, tutor Fortress with Wyvern. If you did not have Fortress at the start of the game, and they removed Fortress after you got it with Wyvern, then you just have to pray.

Usually you can hop around negation with the effects of some of the spells, extra deck monsters, and some of the level 4 monsters like Ancient Gear Tanker. Avoiding, baiting, and overcoming negation and removal is something that is done at your own accord, and you pick and choose the best way you would like to go about overcoming it.

If your opponent has a lot of removal, you can always go into Dingirsu to protect your monsters from removal. You can summon Dingirsu instead of summoning one of the extra deck monsters. Usually, you'll be able to get Dingirsu and Chaos Ancient Gear Giant on the field, but if you're not able to get both then pick your poison.

 

Extra deck monsters:

Chaos Ancient Gear Golem is your main win condition. It is one of the most powerful cards in the deck, and you should always try to get it on the field. It's also unaffected by spell and trap effects, so your opponent can't use removal on it.

Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem is another win condition. The benefit of it is that it can attack three times if summoned with Ancient Gear Duel, and it also has the addition of being able to bring back Ancient Gear Golem if it is destroyed.

Ancient Gear Megaton Golem is good to use if your opponent has lots of destruction. When it leaves the field, it turns into Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem. When Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem is destroyed, it turns into Ancient Gear Golem. Your opponent shouldn't have that much destruction, so you will end up on a good boss monster no matter what.

Ancient Gear Howitzer is a card to use if you're not able to get Fortress up. It is immune to everything, and if it is destroyed, it turns into a Golem or Dark Golem. Also, it does nifty burn damage that I've been able to finish off my opponent with.

Ancient Gear Ballista is good if your opponent has a stupid high attack monster, but it is mainly used for it's effect of popping Geartown.

Gear Gigant X is of a last ditch card. It is useful for getting that one card you need from the deck. For example, if you are missing just one machine monster like Ancient Gear Tanker, then you can get it in your hand with Gigant X.

Aegaion the Sea Castrum is used if your opponent relies on one extra deck monster in their extra deck, or if they are keeping a card in their graveyard to use later. It is also good for that extra deck card removal from the main monster zones.

Qliphort Genius is useful against a single problem monster on your opponent's field. It's also good at getting another Ancient Gear Golem in your hand. It is very situational, and I don't use it much.

Missus Radiant is good in last ditch efforts. If a required machine monster is sent to the graveyard, then you can use her to get that card back. 500 extra attack and defense is a nice bonus, too.

Knightmare Phoenix is only here to remove those pesky spells and traps that are a threat. The second effect of protecting links is good for cards like Apollousa as well, but I have not found myself in that board state before.

If you go first, Apollousa Bow of the Goddess is a grand card to go into if you have extra cards on the field at the end. Having a board of one of the Ancient Gear Fusions and an Apollousa is a good way to end turn 1.

If you go first, Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir is what to put on the field if you don't have anything you can do. If you fail to get any of the fusion monsters on the board and you fail to get a good board, you can just XYZ summon Bagooska into defense position and pray.

If you go first, Abyss Dweller is fairly obvious. If your opponent relies heavily on graveyard effects, then Abyss Dweller is a must play. It is also good going second, but it is more situational.

 

Side decking:

If you want to change anything in the side deck, I would suggest swapping Clockwork Night, Harpie's Feather Duster, or Triple Tactics Talent for either Kaijus, Dark Ruler No More, or Infinite Impermanence. Each of those can stop problem monsters your opponent has. Adding spell and trap removal such as Cosmic Cyclone is also an option.

Going first:

This deck is not good at setting up a board of negations, so if you lose the dice roll, then you will probably lose the game. You can always try to go into Bagooska or Apollousa, but the chances are slim of you surviving to kill your opponent in turn 3.

When siding to go first, you'll want to add a myriad of cards. The first you'll want is Skill Drain. If your opponent can't get rid of it, it is an instant win. Ancient Gear wins with just how big it's walls are. It stops their monster effects which means they can't do their combos and they can't negate you with monster effects.

If your opponent has many pieces of spell negation and powerful spells in general, then Solemn Judgement is your answer. Solemn Judgement is your answer for most of your opponent's big plays. You can stop them before they happen.

Triple Tactics Talent is useful if your opponent tries to stop you in your combo. It allows you to continue it.

Ash Blossom is Ash Blossom. Enough said.

The cards in the main deck I usually swap when going first are: Urgent Schedule, and a few copies of some of the monsters. You can get away with taking away an Ancient Gear Fusion as well.

Going second:

Harpie's Feather Duster is good at removing opponents trap and spell negation all in one go.

Ash Blossom is Ash Blossom.

Clockwork Night is useful for a few reasons. If your opponent is running a deck that requires the cards to be a specific type, then it can shut them down instantly. The second effect of tutoring for any Earth Machine is wonderful as well.

 

I'm sure there are improvements that could be made, and I'm excited to hear suggestions. I love Ancient Gears and they were the very first archetype I played. I'm so happy they're getting support, and I look forward to seeing where the deck goes in the future. I don't expect anything grand or incredible, but I do expect it to be fun!

deck_excerpt: It's an updated deck list for my Sylvan pile, it's probably not the most optimal you can get but I tried to keep it Plant-centric.
deck_description:
There's a lot to this deck, and a lot you can change since Sylvans, and in general, Plants can be very modular in how you build them. Since I last made a deck list for them we've gotten Dancepione, which is by far one of the best support cards for Sylvans and a decent support for Plant decks in general.

Without too much, I'll just give a basic rundown on the deck and what it aims to do:

 

Monsters:

Spore - Spore can be an amazing extender and is one of the more reliable ways to get out Chaos Ruler and get to either Baronne or Chaos Angel, which opens up plays for another Rank-8 and allows for follow-up on following turns should you go first (detach Chaos Ruler > goes into GY and doesn't get banished).

Rose Lover - I left her at 2, she's great for pitching from your hand and extending where you really need to extend, but you don't need her at 3 since she might clog your hand up and doesn't have much use outside of a follow up for your next turn.

Peaskeeper - Peaskeeper is best at 3 I think, you ideally want to be able to summon a few as well as be able to mill it into the GY with a Lonefire already in the GY, which is a target for it.

Cherubsprout - A great card for extending, but doesn't do much unless you can special summon it, I think 2 of it is optimal.

Snapdrassinagon - I added a 2nd copy of it just for more extending, it's great to be able to pitch it and use multiple copies for something like Chaos Ruler, as well for "Lily" Borea since it will pretty much proc for any reason to excavate.

Princessprout - Her at 3 is debatable, you can add in another extender, but 2-3 I would say is probably the sweet spot, she's not a brick or garnet and can get off any plays should you have extenders. Her level modularity also helps the deck into making Synchros and/or Rank-8s.

Rikka Petal - I wouldn't say you need her in the deck honestly (because she locks you into Plants if you search) but she's still good in a pinch, and you have plenty of Plant XYZ to make use of should you get Plant locked.

Lonefire Blossom - Instant 3 of, more chances to put it in the GY from your excavations and it's a fantastic starter.

Peaskeeper - Initially I had it at 3 because he was the only real Normal Summon and has a better chance at hitting than Peaskeeper, but I think 1 is for the best currently, you have plenty of ways to extend and get your plays off, and he doesn't do much if you don't have your Normal Summon aside from be a monster pop at best.

Flowerbot - You can pitch it, get rid of garnets, draw 1, and get a controlled top mill with it, I replaced a copy of Mount Sylvania for it.

Romarin - Aside from Garden Rose Maiden (which I will get to) it's one of your main ways to get Spore and/or Rose Lover into the GY (and if you really need, Lonefire), and it being a Tuner means you can make Synchro plays.

Princess - A great extender + monster negate, helps you get into Dancepione which will be one of your first summons if you can help it. You can make Chaos Ruler with her as well, you just have to summon it by any effect other than her own (Dancepione or Rose Lover).

Sagequoia - I think 3 of him it perfectly fine honestly, though you can run 2 and still be fine, but odds are you want to see at least one of him in your starting hand to extend and maybe even make Chaos Ruler with Spore, which more than likely can get you to any of your level 10 Synchros.

Hermitree - Not completely necessary but does allow you to have a more controlled mill, or lets you know "hey, I probably should shuffle my deck, these are all spells". Going into him off of a Lonefire for Synchro or Rank-8 plays also work, and the extra draw really doesn't hurt.

Snowdrop - Petal and her are the only 2 Plants in the deck that hard lock you into Plants if you use their effects, but most of the time (at least ideally) you'll be something them off of any other effect you can, especially Snowdrop. She makes Synchro and especially Rank-8 plays that much easier, and by extension should you need it, lets you get some extra board space cleared up that way.

"Lily" Borea - A 1-of for her is completely fine, she gets you proc Snap's effect by and can get you started/extend if you really need it.

Mardel - Easily a 1-of, she's a bit of a garnet in your hand and you preferably don't use Rose Lover on her even though she's a search for "Lily" Borea or any other card. Lonefire > Mardel > Search what you need (we'll say Princess) > SS Princess > Dancepione > Continue Combo.

Spells:

Feather Duster - The only real S/T removal this deck has outside of the ED monsters.

Pot of Avarice - I think it's fine as a 1-of, you're able to get to it a decent amount of times off of either Princessprite or Alsei (preferably not Alsei), just good draw power and can help get you back anything you'd want in the deck.

One for One - Easily the best starter in the deck, if you go uninterupted you can usually end on a full board with enough luck.

Sylvan Charity - This is probably going to be Ash'd more than anything else in your deck, so if something is Ash'd, you'd want it to be this. Draw 3 and stack your deck, means getting rid of any garnets like Cherub.

Sylvania - A decent card, but I've opted for 1 copy since we have Flowerbot.

Extra Deck:

Chaos Ruler - Very easy to make and can help you extend quite a lot, on it's own can set up your entire board.

Baronne - You can replace this with Chaos Angel, Dis Pater, or any other Synchro 10 you think will fit, but I've opted for her over Angel just so you can interact more with your opponent.

Princessprite - I'd say 1-2 copies of her is best, you can reset her if you really need and ideally you'll be pushing for game since this deck doens't really have much staying power due to the nature of the deck.

Numeron Dragon - Easy to make with Draglubion and can easily set you up for an OTK, pretty much no matter how strong your opponent's monster is (since you'll have almost no trouble churning out Rank-8s)

Queen Strenna - An easy addition, helps get you to Teardrop just by doing your Jasmine plays, plus lets you add back any Plant from your GY which can help with extending.

Orea - Helps get you a controlled mill and helps you set up plays (you can also use Strenna's effect to get him on the board). It also has a non-targeting bounce of up to 3 cards (yours or your opponents).

Alsei - Instant inclusion, lets you add any card if you really need it and know what you're going to top-deck, and it also lets you bounce an opponent's card for just doing what you were going to do anyways.

Titanic - Another Draglubion target, lets you negate a spell which the deck really struggles with outside of opening the nuts.

Draglubion - Don't ask.

Teardrop - Quick effect tribute an opponent's monster and extremely easy to make, helps with interupting any opponent's plays (and since it sends their monster for cost it won't proc some stuff)

Zeus - For Zeus plays.

Jasmine - Lets you get stuff into the GY and helps you tribute Strenna for a free summon + Rank 5+ XYZ Plant monster, instant inclusion (1 of is fine).

Dancepione - Any 2 Plants makes her and she is bonkers in this deck, getting her off is your main priority since she can get stuff into the GY and special up to 2 bodies.

Apollosa/Underworld Goddess - Apollosa and Goddess are pretty easy to make in this deck and in general are just fine to have, especially if you have free bodies you don't mind giving up.

Icejade Ran Aegirine

(Credit to LukeVonKarma for the inspiration.)

So, you might have heard of "Updraft" from LukeVonKarma's recent replay video, which was shown in the first match. I decided to include my twist with Treasure Panda and I'm so glad I did. Not only I broke the record with millions of damage but I guess I also hit integer overflow, in a way. Anyways, here is how to play.

 

 

Gameplan

1) When Baronne is placed on Main Monster Zone and you have four other monsters, Link Summon Saryuja with them. If you have five, either Link Summon Reprodocus before Saryuja or erase one with Offerings.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup your Primal Seed loop. Also, make sure you have all three Cloudian cards (Smoke+Aerosol+Updraft) in-hand.

3) Play Vertical Landing to replace Baronne with a token and Special Summon Coltwing with Saryuja, which automatically summons two more tokens.

4) The current level of Coltwing is based on the sum of level of tokens and original level of Coltwing. This is addition, which is actually done only by tokens, not setting its level to fixed amount. Therefore, by playing "Galaxy Queen's Light" on Coltwing, its level will increase with respect to level of tokens. Reason is that you will also increase the level of tokens. Here is the process:

  • At first, the level of Coltwing will be level 13 >>> Coltwing (4) + Token (3) + Token (3) + Token (3)
  • Galaxy Queen's Light >>> Target Coltwing (level 13) >>> Tokens will be level 13
  • New calculation = Token (13) + Token (13) + Token (13) + Coltwing (4) = Coltwing (43)

5) Repeat the step explained in #4, by targeting only on Coltwing and nothing else.

6) When you think it's enough or you couldn't play "Galaxy Queen's Light" due to limits, activate "Cloudian Aerosol" to discard "Smoke Ball". Then, target on Chaos Emperor to place lots of Fog Counters. Finally, set "Updraft" and end your turn.

7) On your opponent's turn of Draw Phase, activate "Updraft" to deal millions of damage and win the game!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Cloudian Aerosol" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Baronne de Fleur" can be found within "The Noble Knights of Crimson Flowers" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

Here is a deck based off the Master Duel tutorial involving the Monarchs. They remind me of the bosses in Shadow of the Colossus. Commanding with these super powerful cards would be super fun. The deck focuses a lot on tribute summoning so good luck!

After accumulating lots of counters and launching an atomic bomb, I decided to do it again with a real calculator. Nothing will go wrong with Number 43 at your side.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Throughout the game, discard Coltwing+Calculator with Ravenous and send Number 13 to GY.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup your Primal Seed loop. 

3) Play "Vertical Landing" to replace up to two WIND monsters with tokens. If there is no WIND monster(s), revive up to two of them (Baronne/Martial/Accel/Stardust) with "Monster Reborn". If there are monster(s) other than Chaos and token(s), clear them with "Mystik Wok". Then, revive Coltwing with "Monster Reborn", which also summons up to two tokens.

4) The current level of Coltwing is based on the sum of level of tokens and original level of Coltwing. This is addition, which is actually done only by tokens, not setting its level to fixed amount. Therefore, by playing "Galaxy Queen's Light" on Coltwing, its level will increase with respect to level of tokens. Reason is that you will also increase the level of tokens. Here is the process:

  • At first, the level of Coltwing will be level 13 >>> Coltwing (4) + Token (3) + Token (3) + Token (3)
  • Galaxy Queen's Light >>> Target Coltwing (level 13) >>> Tokens will be level 13
  • New calculation = Token (13) + Token (13) + Token (13) + Coltwing (4) = Coltwing (43)

5) Repeat the step explained in #4, by targeting only on Coltwing and nothing else.

6) When you think it's enough or you couldn't play "Galaxy Queen's Light" due to limits, get rid of Saryuja + Coltwing with "Mystik Wok".

7) Revive Number 13 with "Monster Reborn" and overlay into Number 43 with "Rank-Up-Magic Launch". Place Number 43 on Extra Monster Zone (EMZ). Then, revive "The Calculator" with "Monster Reborn" and play "Galaxy Queen's Light" for one last time to boost "The Calculator".

8) With your monsters having high level amounts and "The Calculator" going off the charts, activate "Mystik Wok" and target on "The Calculator". Choose its ATK and gain lots of LP, which enables Number 43 to reflect said LP as damage to your opponent and let you win the game!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!
